My solution based on custom type `Event` and PriorityQueue

Time Complexity -> O(nlogn), where n is the number of intervals.
Space Complexity -> O(n)

```
class Event {
        int time;
        int order; // +1 for start -1 for end;
        Event(int time, int order) {
            this.time = time;
            this.order = order;
        }
    }

public void getIntervalFrequency(int[][] times) {
        PriorityQueue<Event> events = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b) -> a.time == b.time ? b.order - a.order : a.time - b.time);
        for(int[] time: times) {
            events.add(new Event(time[0], 1));
            events.add(new Event(time[1], -1));
        }
        Event firstEvent = events.poll();
        int prev = firstEvent.time;
        int currentFrequency = firstEvent.order;
        while(!events.isEmpty()) {
            Event event = events.poll();
            System.out.println("["+prev+"->"+event.time+"]" + "->" + currentFrequency);
            currentFrequency += event.order;
            prev = event.time;
        }
    }

Simple O(nlogn) solution which builds a timeline. Similar problem to https://leetcode.com/problems/car-pooling/

```
def interval_count(intervals):
    time_line = {}
    for s,e in intervals:
        if s not in time_line:
            time_line[s] = 0
        if e not in time_line:
            time_line[e] = 0

        time_line[s] += 1
        time_line[e] -= 1

    result = []
    start = None
    count = 0
    for k in sorted(time_line.keys()):
        prev = count
        count += time_line[k]
        if start is not None:
            result.append((start, k, prev))
        start = k

    return result
```

